    "Since the union of a countable sequence of measure-zero sets is a measure-zero set, there exists S ⊆ Ω with P(S) = 1 such that for all ω ∈ S, the equalities in Eq.",
    "(15) hold for all t (the dependence of random variables on ω is omitted for clarity of presentation).",
    "Applying Taylor's expansion pathwise for every ω ∈ S, we get the following:",
    "where ∂ x f t, ∂ y f t, and ∂ z f t denote the partial derivatives of f t 0, Y 0 t-1, I 0 t with respect to its first, second, and third arguments respectively; higher-order derivatives follow the same notation convention.",
    "(16), the term R t collects the unretained second-order terms together with the third-order derivatives of f t as the remainder of our Taylor expansion."
